AttributeValuesData.AttributeValue: This species, also known as Northern White-cedar or Eastern White-cedar is one of eastern North America's longest lived trees; individuals estimated 500-1200 years of age have been identified. The oldest tree in MN is a northern white cedar growing in Lake County estimated at over 1,100 years. This species is very hard and can grown in harsh conditions such as cliffs and overhangs, often taking on curving, gnarled shapes. In Minnesota it is often found in swamps in addition to upland forests, rocky lakeshores, rock outcrops and cliffs. Saplings are very tolerant to shade which gives them an ability to survive for a long time in the forest understory waiting for a gap to open in the canopy. Seeds germinate well on rotting logs and moss.
"Red-brown bark will exfoliate on mature branches and trunks. "
Arborvitae, Eastern White cedar, Northern White Cedar
Cone, 1/4-1/2" long. Brown. Oblong; erect, on curved stalks. 8-12 thin scales. Matures in autumn of first year.

Scalelike, tiny, 1/8-1/4" long. Yellow-green above, paler beneath, each leaf has resin gland. Leaves in four rows along somewhat flattened branchlet. Foliage splays flattened, fanlike. Bronze-tinged in autumn.
Ability to live for centuries, small scalelike leaves on soft, flat "splays"
